06709nam a2200829Ia 9781478024545DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780245457 a10.1515/97814780245452doi  a(DE-B1597)664252  a(OCoLC)1379845546  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04aThe Cunning of Gender Violence :bGeopolitics and Feminism /ced. by Nadera Shalhoub-Kevorkian, Lila Abu-Lughod, Rema Hammami. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (480 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNext Wave: New Directions in Women's Studies : 4400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: Circuits of Power in GBVAW Governance -- tI. Securitization -- t1. Lawfare, CVE, and International Conflict Feminism -- t2. Securofeminism -- t3. The Role of “Honor Killings” in the Muslim Ban -- t4. Because Religion -- tII. States of Violence, Unruly Subjects -- t5. GBV and Postcolonial India -- t6. The Politics of Legislating “Honor Crime” in Contemporary Pakistan -- t7. State Criminality and Gender-Based Violence -- t8. Power, Subjectivity, and Sexuality in Iranian Political Prisons -- tIII. Civilizing Interventions: Development and Humanitarianism -- t9. Child Marriage in the Feminist Imagination -- t10. Catastrophic Aid -- t11. What Counts as Violence? -- tIV. Media Frames -- t12. Weaponized Bodies -- t13. Breaking the Frame -- t14. Dressed Up, Stripped Down -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Cunning of Gender Violence focuses on how a once visionary feminist project has folded itself into contemporary world affairs. Combating violence against women and gender-based violence constitutes a highly visible and powerful agenda enshrined in international governance and law and embedded in state violence and global securitization. Case studies on Palestine, Bangladesh, Iran, India, Pakistan, Israel, and Turkey as well as on UN and US policies trace the silences and omissions, along with the experiences of those subjected to violence, to question the rhetoric that claims the agenda as a “feminist success story.” Because religion and racialized ethnicity, particularly “the Muslim question,” run so deeply through the institutional structures of the agenda, the contributions explore ways it may be affirming or enabling rationales and systems of power, including civilizational hierarchies, that harm the very people it seeks to protect.Contributors. Lila Abu-Lughod, Nina Berman, Inderpal Grewal, Rema Hammami, Janet R. Jakobsen, Shenila Khoja-Moolji, Vasuki Nesiah, Samira Shackle, Sima Shakhsari, Nadera Shalhoub-Kevorkian, Dina M Siddiqi, Shahla Talebi, Leti Volpp, Rafia Zakaria  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSexual minoritiesxViolence againstxReligious aspects. 0aSexual minoritiesxViolence against. 0aWomenxViolence againstxGovernment policy. 0aWomenxViolence againstxReligious aspects. 0aWomenxViolence against. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aAbu-Lughod, Lila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbu-Lughod, Lila, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerman, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrewal, Inderpal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammami, Rema, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammami, Rema, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJakobsen, Janet R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhoja-Moolji, Shenila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul